# Public Prosecutor _v_ Erh Zhi Huang, Alvan  

### \[2022\] SGDC 251

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Statutory Offences – Road Traffic Act – Driving without due care and attention and causing grievous hurt

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9204/2022/01.\]

28 October 2022

### District Judge Salina Bte Ishak:

## Background

1       The accused, Mr Erh Zhi Huang, Alvan, a 30-year-old male Singapore citizen, was first charged on 8 June 2022 for the following offence:

Charge

> are charged that on 30th August 2021 at or about 6.56 pm, along Pan Island Expressway towards Tuas, near to 19 km, Singapore, did drive a motor vehicle SJN214H on a road without due care and attention, to wit, by failing to keep a proper lookout when changing lanes and resulting in a collision with motorcycle, JGJ4651 which was travelling on your left, and grievous hurt was caused to one Ho Yong Siang/Male/48 years old, by such driving, you have thereby committed an offence under Section 65(1)(a) punishable under Section 65(3)(a) read with Section 65(6)(d) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”).

2       On 11 October 2022, the accused pleaded guilty to the charge and admitted to the Statement of Facts without any qualification. After carefully considering the Prosecution’s address on sentence and the Defence’s plea in mitigation, I sentenced the accused to ten weeks’ imprisonment and disqualified him from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of five years with effect from the date of release.

3       On 11 October 2022, the accused being dissatisfied with my decision filed his Notice of Appeal against my sentence. He is presently on bail pending the hearing of his appeal.

4       Having set out the background for the present case, I now provide the reasons for my decision.

## Salient Facts

5       The accused was the driver of motorcar, SJN214H, at the time of accident. The victim is Ho Yong Siang, Male Chinese, Malaysian, 48 years old. He was the rider of motorcycle, JGJ4651, at the time of accident.

6       On 30 August 2021 at about 6.56pm, the accused drove his motorcar along lane 1 of the three-lane Pan Island Expressway towards Tuas. The victim rode behind the accused in lane 2. There was another car travelling in front of the accused. This car braked and came to a stop due to heavy traffic in front of it. The accused then abruptly switched lanes from lane 1 to lane 2. The accused did drive without due care and attention, by failing to keep a proper lookout when changing lanes and resulting in a collision with the victim who was travelling on the accused’s left on lane 2, and grievous hurt was caused to the victim. At the time of accident, the weather was clear, the road surface was dry and the traffic flow was heavy.

7       As a result of the accident, the victim was sent to Tan Tock Seng Hospital (TTSH) by ambulance. He was discharged on 31 August 2021 and given hospitalisation leave from 30 August 2021 to 8 September 2021 and from 9 September 2021 to 24 September 2021. This was further extended to 19 October 2021 and thereafter to 26 October 2021. A total of 58 days of hospitalisation leave was given.

8       The victim sustained the following injuries:

> (a)     Traumatic amputation of the right little finger; and

> (b)     Right sided clavicle fracture.

The victim had a terminalisation of the right little finger performed.

9       As a result of the accident, the victim’s motorcycle was damaged:

> (a)     Cracks, scratches and dents at the front of the motorcycle;

> (b)     Dangling front head lamp;

> (c)     Scratches on the front mudguard;

> (d)     Broken left handle;

> (e)     Dented right handle grip stopper; and

> (f)     Scratches on the right of the rear box.

10     The accused’s car was also damaged. There were dents on the left rear door and scratches on the left front door.

11     By virtue of the foregoing, the accused has committed an offence under Section 65(1) (a) punishable under Section 65(3)(a) and Section 65(6)(d) of the Road Traffic Act, Chapter 276.

## Sentencing

## Prescribed Penalty

12     The prescribed penalty for an offence under s 65(1)(_b_) and punishable ss 65(3)(_a_) read with 65(6)(_d_) of the RTA is fine not exceeding $5,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 2 years or to both. In addition, the offender is liable to a mandatory disqualification order for all classes of vehicles for at least five years.

## Antecedents

13     The accused has no prior convictions.

## Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

14     The Prosecution had submitted that it was not objecting to a short detention order (''SDO'') and the minimum of at least five years' disqualification. It was the Prosecution’s position that if an SDO is imposed, the duration would be left to the Court's discretion.

15     In its address on sentence, the Prosecution had relied on the five-step sentencing framework for offences under s 65(3)(_a_) of the RTA laid down by the High Court in _Sue Chang (Xu Zheng) v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 176</span> (“_Sue Chang_”). The steps are as follows:

> (a)     First step: Identifying the level of harm and level of culpability.

> (b)     Second step: Identifying the applicable indicative sentencing range in the sentencing matrix.

![](data:image;base64,)

> (c)     Third step: Identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range.

> (d)     Fourth step: Make adjustments to the starting point to take into account offender-specific factors.

> (e)     Fifth step: Make adjustments for totality principle.

16     It was submitted that in determining the levels of harm, the High Court at \[87\] gave the following guidance:

> (a)      _Low_: Managed with conservative treatment, with no or short periods of hospitalisation and/or medical leave. The harm occasioned would typically involve minor fractures/dislocation at less vulnerable parts of the body.

> (b)      _Moderate_: The injuries are of a more permanent nature and/or involve more complex fractures/dislocation which necessitate some surgical procedures with a moderate period of hospitalisation and/or medical leave.

> (c)      _Serious_: The injuries are of a very serious or permanent nature and/or necessitate significant surgical procedures. The victim’s daily living is usually permanently and severely affected. This includes injuries resulting in loss of limb, sight, hearing, member or other major bodily functions or paralysis.

17     It was the Prosecution’s position that the level of harm was moderate to serious. The victim suffered serious damage to his right little finger which required surgical intervention of a traumatic amputation. In addition to this, the victim also suffered a right sided clavicle fracture. The victim was given a total of 58 days of hospitalization leave.

18     As for culpability, the Prosecution acknowledged that there were no other culpability increasing factors. The accused immediately rendered assistance to the victim at the scene of accident. It was submitted that the level of culpability ought to be low.

19     Applying the matrix, it was further submitted the indicative sentencing range should be from a fine and up to 8 months’ imprisonment.

20     As for the third step, this is to be informed by the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of the offender’s culpability (\[105\] of _Sue Chang_). It was the Prosecution’s position that the appropriate starting point would be a short custodial sentence _ie_ the upper end of low culpability-moderate harm and lower end of low culpability-serious harm.

21     As for the fourth step, the Prosecution noted the following offender-specific factors:

> (a)     the accused possessed a completely clean driving record at the time of the offence; and

> (b)     he elected to plead guilty at an early opportunity.

22     The Prosecution had submitted that an SDO would be appropriate to address the accused's prospects for rehabilitation. It was submitted that that such a sentencing outcome would also be in line with the following precedents:

## Mitigation

23     In his written plea in mitigation, it was highlighted that the accused had admitted to the Statement of Facts without any qualification. The Court was urged to accept his timely plea of guilt as a sign of his contrition and regret for the wrong he had done. He admitted that he should not have committed the acts in question and his actions were a lapse of judgment. This was a scar that would remain with him for the rest of his life.

24     It was submitted that his timely plea of guilt had saved the Court’s time and resources. He had fully cooperated with the police in their investigations. He had been candid and forthright in giving his statements. He has no antecedents and this was his first brush with the law.

25     It was further submitted that the accused is gainfully employed as a regular in the Singapore Armed Forces (SAF). He is a young and bright individual who is a credit to the defence force of Singapore. He understood that the repercussions following the court proceedings could derail his career. He remained fully committed to his work despite these trying times.

26     It was the Defence’s position that the accused understood the seriousness of the offence and was not making any excuses for what he did. He realised the gravity of his actions and was deeply apologetic about it. It was submitted that he was highly repentant and has no intention of reoffending. The accused had been very honest in providing the full account to the authorities. His overestimation of his readiness at the material time was what that led to his mistake. This was completely out of character for the dedicated serviceman. He pleaded with the Court for leniency and a second chance to start anew. Hence, the Defence sought the imposition of seven days of SDO.

## Sentencing considerations

### S 65(1) of the RTA

27     The present offence under s 65(1) of the RTA was enacted on 1 November 2019, following the passing of the Road Traffic (Amendment) Act 2019 (Act 19 of 2019). S 65(1) of the RTA encapsulates the primary offence of driving without due care or reasonable consideration for other persons using the road. The subsequent subsections from ss 65(2) to 65(4) are the penalty prescribing provisions, each tiered according to the degree of hurt caused and for s 65(5), for any other case of non-personal injury or potential harm.

#### Sentencing approach

28     In the present case, I was bound by the sentencing framework prescribed by Justice Vincent Hoong (“Justice Hoong”) in _Sue Chang_ for offences of driving without due care and attention and causing grievous hurt. The sentencing framework for offences under section 65(3)(_a_) of the RTA where the offender has claimed trial is set out at \[15\] above.

29     At \[65\] of his judgment, Justice Hoong opined that the most suitable sentencing approach to adopt in respect of offences under s 65(3)(_a_) of the RTA is the two-stage, five-step sentencing framework laid down by Menon CJ in _Logachev Vladislav v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 4 SLR 609</span> at \[75\](“_Logachev_\-hybrid approach”). At \[84\] to \[108\] of his judgment, Hoong J had set out the five steps to be taken namely:

> (a)     The first step is to identify the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of culpability of the offender. The harm caused by the offence may be categorised into three levels of increasing severity: low, moderate and serious. Likewise, the offender’s culpability may be categorised into three levels: low, moderate and high. The non-exhaustive list of factors within the broad categories of harm and culpability which fashion the two axes of the matrix are:

> **_1) Factors going to harm_**

> The degree of harm caused would generally refer to the nature and degree of the grievous bodily injury caused to the victim(s): see _Tang Ling Lee_ v PP <span class="citation">\[2018\] 4 SLR 813</span> at \[25\] (“_Tang Ling Lee_”). The levels of harm can be divided based on the severity of the grievous hurt suffered as follows:

>> (i)        _Low_: The hurt caused can be managed with conservative treatment, with no or short periods of hospitalisation and/or medical leave. The harm occasioned would typically involve minor fractures/dislocation at less vulnerable parts of the body.

>> (ii)        _Moderate_: The injuries are of a more permanent nature and/or involve more complex fractures/dislocation which necessitate some surgical procedures with a moderate period of hospitalisation and/or medical leave.

>> (iii)        _Serious_: The injuries are of a very serious or permanent nature and/or necessitate significant surgical procedures. The victim’s daily living is usually permanently and severely affected. This includes injuries resulting in loss of limb, sight, hearing, member or other major bodily functions or paralysis.

>> In addition, there are two other factors which may contribute to the severity of the harm caused, namely: (a) property damage; and (b) potential harm. These factors are to be considered in tandem with the above descriptions of each level of harm.

> **_2) Factors going to culpability_**

> This can be measured based on the following factors:

>> (a)       Circumstances which required the offender to exercise extra care or consideration. Some examples of these circumstances include where the offender drives: (i) within a school or residential zone; (ii) a heavy vehicle that is more difficult to control and requires a quicker reaction time; or (iii) in poor road conditions (_eg_ heavy rain or heavy traffic);

>> (b)       The manner of driving. Under this factor, it is apposite to consider any dangerous driving behaviour exhibited by the offender. This would include, for example, driving against the flow of traffic, speeding, sleepy driving, drink-driving, driving while under the influence of drugs, driving while using a mobile phone, flouting traffic rules, or “hell-riding” situations: see _Tang Ling Lee_ at \[28\]. In addition, considerations pertaining to the duration of the offender’s inattention (_eg_ momentary or prolonged/sustained), the avoidability of the offender’s distraction or the reasonableness of the offender’s misjudgement are also relevant;

>> (c)       The offender’s conduct following the offence. An offender’s conduct that is “belligerent or violent” upon arrest would constitute an aggravating factor: see _Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> (“_Suse Nathen_”) at \[32\]. Where the offender fails to stop in an attempt to evade arrest or to avoid apprehension by the authorities, this should also weigh against him: see _Public Prosecutor v Lee Meng Soon_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] 4 SLR(R) 240</span> at \[33\].

> (b)     The second step is to identify the applicable indicative sentencing range in the sentencing matrix. Any term of imprisonment imposed may be accompanied by a fine of up to $5,000, if appropriate, as this is explicitly provided for in s 65(3)(_a_) of the RTA. The sentencing judge should be alive to the possibility of imposing such a combination of punishments in order to properly take into account the full sentencing range prescribed by Parliament. Hoong J opined that Parliament has stressed the importance of both harm and culpability and did not suggest that one factor should be given more weight in the sentencing analysis than the other. He emphasized that the proposed sentencing framework and the corresponding indicative ranges set out above are concerned solely with section 65(3)(a) of the RTA.

> (c)     The third step is to identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range. This is to be informed by the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of the offender’s culpability.

> (d)     The fourth step is to make adjustments to the starting point where necessary to take into account the offender-specific aggravating and mitigating factors: see _Ng Kean Meng Terence v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 2 SLR 449</span> (“Terence Ng”) at \[62\]-\[71\].

> (e)     The fifth step is to make further adjustments to take into account the totality principle. This step is relevant only where an offender is faced with multiple charges. It requires the court to consider the need to make further adjustments to the individual sentences for each charge to take into account the totality principle. The totality principle has been expressed in _Mohamed Shouffee bin Adam v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 2 SLR 998</span> at \[54\] and \[57\] as comprising two limbs. The first limb examines whether the aggregate sentence is substantially above the normal level of sentences for the most serious of the individual offences committed. The second limb considers whether the effect of the sentence on the offender is crushing and not in keeping with his past record and his future prospects.

## The sentence

30     I now turn to the facts of the present case and the application of the _Sue Chang_ sentencing framework. The first step is to identify the level of harm and level of culpability of the accused.

#### Culpability

31     In the present case, I was of the view that the accused's culpability was at the higher end of low level as this was an instance where he had failed to keep a proper lookout and ensured that it was safe to do so before abruptly changing lanes from lane 1 to lane 2 along an expressway with heavy traffic. At the material time, the victim was travelling on the accused’s left on lane 2. As there were dents on the left rear door and scratches on the left front door of the accused’s motorcar, this would have been the point of impact with the victim’s motorcycle. In my view, it was clear that the accused had displayed a high degree of carelessness as he failed to ensure that there was sufficient space for him to safely make the lane change before doing so, leaving the hapless victim with little or no time to react to the accused’s motorcar encroaching into his path of travel.

32     Nevertheless, I was mindful that there were also no other culpability enhancing factors such as excessive speeding or deliberate dangerous driving such as in ''hell riding'' cases present in this case which would have brought his culpability to the moderate level.

#### Harm

33     In terms of the degree of harm caused, in determining the degree of harm, I was guided by the definition in _Sue Chang_ at \[87\] where it states that serious injury are injuries that are of a very serious or permanent nature and/or necessitate significant surgical procedures. The victim’s daily living is usually permanently and severely affected. This includes injuries resulting in loss of limb, sight, hearing, member or other major bodily functions or paralysis.

34     In the present case, I was of the view that the injuries fell within the low end of the serious category as the victim suffered a traumatic amputation of his right little finger and a right sided clavicle fracture. A terminalisation of his right little finger was performed. The victim was hospitalised for one day and was given 58 days of hospitalisation leave. Hence, I disagreed with the Prosecution that the degree of harm had straddled both the moderate and serious category.

35     In addition, I had considered two other factors which contributed to the severity of the harm caused, namely the property damage to the victim's motorcycle and the level of potential harm. In the present case, the extent of the property damage to the victim's motorcycle has been set out at paragraph 9 of the Statement of Facts. In terms of potential harm, I had considered the fact that the offence was committed on a weekday _ie_ a Monday on 30 August 2021 at about 6.56 pm during heavy evening traffic along a major expressway where the speed limit was 90 km/h. The vehicles on the expressway would have been travelling at higher average speeds and the flow of traffic was fast as compared to an average road. Under such conditions, the level of potential harm to other road users under such circumstances would be serious.

36     It is not uncommon to see chain collisions on our expressways where physical harm or property damage or both are occasioned due to sudden stoppages resulting from emergency braking by the other vehicles or any accidents ahead.

#### The second step

37     The second step is to identify the indicative sentencing range in the sentencing matrix. In the present case as the level of culpability was at the higher end of low and the level of harm at the lower end of serious, I was of the view that it fell between the sentencing range of 4 to 8 months imprisonment.

#### Third step

38     The third step is identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range. In the present case, the appropriate starting point would be four months’ imprisonment as the accused’s level of culpability was at the higher end of low while the harm at the lower end of serious.

#### Fourth step

39     The fourth step is to make the necessary adjustments to the starting point to take into account the offender-specific factors. The fifth step is not applicable in the present case as the accused had pleaded guilty to a single charge of driving without due care and attention and caused grievous hurt. As such, no adjustments are necessary to take into account the totality principle.

40     The accused is a 30-year-old army regular who had pleaded guilty to a single charge and was untraced. Nevertheless, he is clearly a mature working adult and not a young offender unlike the accused persons in the precedents referred to by the Prosecution, who were between 20 to 21 years old at the time of offences.

41     In my view, the primary sentencing objective for the present charge is that of deterrence and the protection of the public, particularly considering the seriousness of the offence and the degree of harm caused to the victim. The fact that the present offence attracts a specified period of disqualification of not less than five years, is an indicator of the significant primacy accorded to the objective of protecting other road users from such offenders. Based on the level of culpability and the degree of harm, the usual sentence would be a custodial sentence as well as a disqualification of at least five years from date of release. In the present case, I note that it was the Prosecution’s own position that the custodial threshold had been crossed and that the appropriate starting point would be a short custodial sentence.

42     Nevertheless, in the present case the Prosecution then went on to depart from its usual sentencing position for cases with similar factual matrix and had instead sought for a community-based sentence (“CBS”) in the form of a short detention order (“SDO”). It was the Prosecution’s position that such a sentence would be appropriate to address the accused's prospects for rehabilitation and such a sentencing outcome would also be in line with the precedents cited in support as set out at \[22\] above.

#### Whether CBS is appropriate

43     In the present case, I had to determine whether the accused, who was 29 years’ old at the time of offending, was a suitable candidate for a CBS. I first considered the legislative intent underlying the CBS framework. CBSs were introduced to allow greater flexibility in balancing the various sentencing principles in individual cases. CBS targets offences and offenders traditionally viewed by the courts to be on the rehabilitation end of the spectrum: _ie_, regulatory offences, offences involving younger accused persons and persons with specific and minor mental conditions (_Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report_ (18 May 2010) vol 87 at col 422 (K Shanmugam, Minister for Law and Second Minister for Home Affairs).

44     I was mindful that in _Sim Wen Yi Ernest v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2016\] 5 SLR 207</span> at \[40\] to \[41\], See Kee Oon JC (as he then was) had stated that:

> 40    The important point that emerges from the above authorities is that the suitability of the various types of CBS orders depends on the type of offender and the type of offence. This calls for an open-textured assessment that is highly contextualised and the court must have regard to all the facts of the case. Some types of CBS may have greater relevance in the cases which involve youthful offenders since such offenders are often seen to have greater rehabilitative capacity. Nevertheless, I did not think that offenders over the age of 21 should _ipso facto_ be denied the opportunity to be considered for CBS. The rehabilitative aim does not automatically recede into the background once the offender reaches 21 years of age. In every case, the particular circumstances of the offence and the offender in question must be carefully scrutinised and evaluated to determine whether rehabilitation should be given prominence notwithstanding any countervailing need for deterrence, retribution or prevention: _Kalaiarasi_ (\[23\] _supra_) at \[39\]. Thus, the appropriateness of CBS is a question which turns on _all_ the relevant circumstances of each case, including the offence and offender in question.

> 41    This approach is consistent with ss 346 and 348 of the CPC which provide that persons above 16 years of age can be considered for CSOs and SDOs respectively; the provisions do not restrict the imposition of such orders to offenders below the age of 21. It is also in line with the broad policy objective that undergirds the CBS framework, that is, to enable offenders of less serious crimes to be dealt with in ways other than by imposing fines or imprisonment to enhance their chances of rehabilitation without diluting the deterrent objective of our penal regime or jeopardising the public’s sense of safety (Sentencing Practice in the Subordinate Courts Volume 1 (LexisNexis, 3rd Ed, 2013) (“Sentencing Practice in the Subordinate Courts”) at p 77).

45     A community-based sentence targets offences and offenders traditionally viewed by the court to be on the rehabilitative end of the spectrum such as regulatory offences, offences involving younger accused persons and persons with specific and minor mental conditions, where it is appropriate to harness the resources of the community: _GCX v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] 3 SLR 1325</span> (''_GCX_'').

46     After having carefully considered all the relevant circumstances of the present case, including the offence and the offender in question to determine whether rehabilitation should be given prominence notwithstanding any countervailing need for deterrence, retribution or prevention, I was of the view the accused was not a suitable candidate for a CBS. As stated above, I was of the view that deterrence and the protection of the public were the main sentencing consideration in view of the seriousness of the offence and the degree of harm caused to the victim. The accused is not a younger accused person, it was not a regulatory offence and there was no evidence that the accused had any mental specific or minor mental condition. Furthermore, no justification was provided by either the Prosecution or the Defence as to why rehabilitation was considered to be a dominant sentencing consideration which eclipsed that of deterrence and the protection of the public.

#### Disqualification order

47     In deciding on the appropriate period of disqualification, I was mindful that the disqualification order and the sentence imposed are not mutually compensatory.

48     In determining the appropriate length of the disqualification order, I was guided by the approach in the recent case of _Kwan Weiguang v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 121</span> (“_Kwan_”). Although Justice Aedit Abdullah dealt with an appeal against a disqualification order of 15 months that was imposed on the appellant for an offence of dangerous driving under s 64(1) and punishable under s 64(2C)(_a_) of the RTA, the factors considered are relevant to the present case. He held at \[59\] and \[61\] that the objective of the disqualification order is as follow:

> A driving disqualification order combines three sentencing objectives: punishment, protection of the public and deterrence (_Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> (“_Edwin Nathen_”) at \[13\]). Often, due to the limited range of fines in the punishment provision, the impact of a disqualification order is likely to be felt much more acutely than any marginal increase in the quantum of the fine (see Edwin Nathen at \[13\])…

> 61    A disqualification order also serves to remove the privilege to drive from those who have abused it, and this also reinforces the notion of shared usage of the roads. It must be remembered that driving is an inherently dangerous activity. The licence to drive is a privilege accorded to persons who, through a series of properly administered tests, have demonstrated that they are capable of meeting the standards expected of a reasonably competent driver (_Jali bin Mohd Yunos v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 4 SLR 1059</span> at \[36\]). The former Minister for Home Affairs, Prof S Jayakumar, had expressed the following view which reinforces this notion (see Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report (28 March 1990) vol 55 at col 960): “… we must get every driver in Singapore to note that when he is issued a licence, it is in fact a very special privilege and it is granted on condition that he drives in a responsible manner bearing in mind the interest of others.”

49     In _Kwan_ at \[65\] to \[71\], the relevant and material factors when determining the period of disqualification are:

> (a)     Circumstances of the commission of the offence and

> (b)     Continued ability to drive and attitude towards other road users.

50     In the present case, the accident occurred when the accused failed to keep a proper lookout and ensure that it was safe to do so before abruptly changing lanes from lane 1 to lane 2 along an expressway with heavy traffic. This resulted in a collision with the victim, who was travelling on the accused’s left on lane 2, and grievous hurt was caused to the victim.

51     In terms of potential harm, as stated earlier, the accident occurred on a weekday at about 6.56pm during heavy evening traffic along a major expressway where the speed limit was 90 km/h. Vehicles would have been travelling at higher average speeds and the flow of traffic was fast as compared to an average road. Under such conditions, the level of potential harm to other road users, who were travelling in the same direction and within the vicinity, would be serious.

52     It was clear that in the present case it was within the public’s interest to remove such a driver from the roads for a substantial period of time. Hence, I was of the view that the minimum disqualification period of five years with effect from the date of release was appropriate as there were no special reasons before me not to make the order or to order a period less than the specified period of five years.

53     All things considered, I was of the view that the sentence of ten weeks’ imprisonment and a disqualification from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of five years in respect of DAC 9207566-2021 was just and appropriate in the circumstances.
